Feature: bc-container launch --startup-prompt's autonomous-engagement guarantee is observable on the monitor surface within a bounded interval

  Sibling pin to scenario 27 (features/bc-launcher/27-launch-with-startup-prompt-submits-prompt-autonomously.gherkin). Scenario 27 pins the behavior — the prompt is committed such that the agent processes it without further input — by reference to the agent's input-loop state. This scenario pins the *observability* of that behavior on the lead-host-reachable contract surface, so that the prompt-submission regression that reproduced under lead-xsmn (prompt visible in input buffer, agent not engaged) is detectable from the host without attaching into the container.

  The contract surface for observation is "bc-container monitor", which streams the tmux pane's rendered output. "The agent has begun processing the prompt" is operationalized as a visible state-marker line in the streamed output that an idle, unsubmitted-buffer state does not produce — concretely, the agent's working/thinking indicator line (e.g. "Working… (thinking)" or the equivalent rendered by the agent runtime) appearing on the monitor stream after the launch command has exited.

  Scenario: bc-container monitor surfaces an agent-working state-marker within a bounded interval of bc-container launch --startup-prompt exiting, with no human or host-side follow-up keystroke
    Given the shopsystem-bc-launcher BC is installed
    And no Docker container named "bc-shopsystem-messaging" is running
    When I run "bc-container launch shopsystem-messaging --startup-prompt 'bd prime'" and the launch command exits zero
    And I run "bc-container monitor shopsystem-messaging" and read its streamed output without issuing any further "bc-container inject" or other host-side keystroke
    Then within 30 seconds of the launch command exiting, the streamed monitor output contains an agent-working state-marker line that is produced only when the agent has committed input and is actively processing it (and not produced when the agent is idle at an unsubmitted input buffer)
    And the agent-working state-marker appears as a direct consequence of the launch's --startup-prompt being submitted, with no intervening "bc-container inject" invocation
